-- FACTBOX-Corporate impact of Boeing's 787 Dreamliner
-- 
-- Sun Jul 8, 2007 2:38pm EDT
-- http://www.reuters.com/article/2007/07/08/us-boeing-787-companies-idUSN0825135120070708

 

 NEW YORK  (Reuters) - Boeing Co. ( BA.N ) unveils its 787 Dreamliner on Sunday. Here are a few of the companies buying, supplying or competing against the new plane. 

 -- The 787 will chiefly compete for sales against Airbus' A350 XWB (extra wide body). Airbus is a unit of European aerospace group EADS ( EAD.PA ). -- Japanese textile firm Toray Industries ( 3402.T ) is supplying the carbon-composite fiber which will make up around half the plane's main structure -- Boeing has orders for 677 Dreamliners from 47 different customers, worth more than $100 billion. -- The first order, for 50 787s, was placed by Japan's All Nippon Airways ( 9202.T ) in July 2004. -- Other large customers include International Lease Finance Corp. ( AIG.N ) (74), Qantas Airways Ltd. ( QAN.AX ) (45), Air Canada ( ACb.TO ) (37), Japan Airlines (JAL) 9205.T (35), Air India AI.UL (27) and Continental Airlines CAL.N (25). -- Boeing is offering a choice of engines by General Electric Co. ( GE.N ) or Britain's Rolls-Royce plc ( RR.L ). -- The main overseas partners on the 787 project are the Japanese "heavies" -- Mitsubishi Heavy Industries Ltd. ( 7011.T ), Kawasaki Heavy Industries Ltd. ( 7012.T ) and Fuji Heavy Industries Ltd. ( 7270.T ), which are building key parts of the carbon composite fuselage, wing box and wing. -- Global Aeronautica is putting together parts of the fuselage in South Carolina. The company is a joint venture between Alenia, a unit of Italian aerospace group Finmeccanica ( SIFI.MI ), and Vought Aircraft Industries Inc., which is majority-owned by private equity firm Carlyle Group CYL.UL. -- Spirit Aerosystems ( SPR.N ) is building fuselage and wing parts. -- Honeywell International Inc. ( HON.N ) and Rockwell Collins Inc. ( COL.N ) are supplying flight control electronics, navigation systems and displays. -- Hamilton Sundstrand, a unit of United Technologies Corp. ( UTX.N ), is making the plane's internal power systems. Sources: Reuters/Boeing